  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony under both federal and state laws in the United States, as well as in many other countries. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal acts) appear legitimate by disguising its true origin. It is a serious crime because it enables criminal enterprises to profit from and perpetuate their illegal activities.\n\nIn the U.S., the federal **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)** makes it a felony to engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from certain criminal activities. Penalties can include:\n\n- Up to **20 years in prison** for each offense.\n- Substantial **fines** (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved, whichever is greater).\n- **Forfeiture of assets** tied to the illegal activity.\n\nAdditionally, state laws may impose their own penalties for money laundering, which can also include felony charges. The severity of the punishment often depends on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the defendant's role in the scheme.\n\nMoney laundering is also a crime under international law, and many countries have enacted legislation to combat it, often in coordination with global anti-money laundering (AML) initiatives.",
